Kenya on Friday recorded 50 new Covid-19 cases from a sample size of 1,583 tested in the last 24 hours. The positivity rate is now at 3.2 per cent. The Health ministry said in a statement 45 of the new cases are Kenyans while five are foreigners. In terms of gender, 22 are males while 28 are females. The youngest is four months old while the oldest is 102 years old. CS Mutahi Kagwe said total confirmed positive cases now stand at 337,550 while 3,818,074 cumulative tests have been conducted so far. "Nairobi accounted for 16, Nakuru 10, Uasin Gishu six, Siaya five, Kiambu four, Busia, Homa Bay and Taita Taveta had two cases each. Kirinyaga, Makueni and Mombasa had one case each," Kagwe said. He said that 106 patients have recovered from the disease, all from the Home Based and Isolation Program. This pushes the total recoveries 331,234 of whom 277,699 are from the Home Based Isolation and Care Program while 53,535 are from health facilities countrywide. No death was reported meaning the number of fatalities still stands at 5,672. "There are 55 patients currently admitted in our health facilities while 589 are under the Home Based Isolation and Care Program. There is no patient in the Intensive Care Unit (ICU)," Kagwe said. "Another 13 are in the General Wards and are all on supplemental oxygen," he added. No patient is in the High Dependency Unit (HDU). As of July 28, a total of 20,142,950 vaccines had been administered across the country. Those administered in the last 24 hours were 153,569 while fully vaccinated adults are 42,277. The proportion of vaccinated adults is 33.5 per cent. The government is working towards vaccinating 27, 246, 033 people by December, 2022.